{"title_page": "International Legal Foundation", "text_new": "{{DISPLAYTITLE:The International Legal Foundation}}\n\n'''The International Legal Foundation (ILF)''' is an [[international non-governmental organization]] founded in 2001. It is focused on establishing and strengthening criminal legal aid systems around the world. In addition to its technical assistance work with foreign governments, the ILF provides direct legal aid services through its multiple in-country offices. To date, ILF lawyers have defended more than 60,000 accused individuals worldwide.\n\n== Founding ==\nWhile serving as an observer to the [[Rwandan genocide|Rwandan genocide trials]], attorney Natalie Rea noticed there were \u201ca handful\u201d defense lawyers available<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://soundslikeportraits.com/natalie-rea-lawyer|title=Sounds Like Portraits: Natalie Rea, criminal defense lawyer: 'I basically don't trust authority\"|website=soundslikeportraits.com}}</ref> to represent the over 70,000 incarcerated at Kigali Central Prison. <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=5NdtfmzesHc|title=RWANDA: REPORT FROM KIGALI CENTRAL PRISON, AP Archive}}</ref> She returned home to the [[United States]] and founded Legal Aid Rwanda <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://dev2019.oakfnd.org/international-human-rights-heroes-natalie-rea/|title=International Human Rights Heroes: NATALIE REA|date=June 20, 2016}}</ref>, which recruited lawyers to travel to [[Rwanda]] and provide pretrial defense. In 2001, Rea founded the International Legal Foundation. Rea created the ILF to address legal aid crises in foreign countries, and expand criminal defense services for the indigent. <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.court-access.org/our-team-2|title=Our Board|website=The Court-Access Project}}</ref> She served as its Executive Director until 2012, when she was succeeded by current director Jennifer Smith. According to its website, Rea now serves as a Senior Advisor on its Board of Directors. <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.theilf.org/natalie-rae|title=Natalie Rea|website=The ILF}}</ref>\n\n== Programs and work abroad ==\nThe majority of ILF programs and staff are located outside of the United States, primarily in its program countries. The ILF has six primary areas of focus: legal aid access; pretrial justice reform; gender equality; racial, ethnic and religious minorities; children and youth; and the [[Sustainable Development Goals|UN SDG16+ framework]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.theilf.org/areas-of-focus|title=Areas of Focus|website=The ILF}}</ref>\nThe ILF hires lawyers local to each country of operation and trains them in legal aid best practices. ILF staff members work with governments globally, sharing their expertise to promote criminal justice reform.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.globalcitizen.org/en/partners/the-international-legal-foundation/|title=The International Legal Foundation|website=Global Citizen}}</ref> Coordination of all programs is carried out from its US Headquarters, which are located in [[New York City]]. <ref>[https://www.guidestar.org/profile/13-4193728 Guidestar Profile]</ref> Its year-round international fellowship program stations experienced defense lawyers from around the world in program countries, to train ILF lawyers in criminal defense and provide additional support to the legal aid office.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.theilf.org/international-fellowships|title=Become a Fellow|website=The ILF}}</ref>\n\n=== Country offices ===\nILF programs are currently active in [[Afghanistan]], [[Myanmar]], [[Nepal]], [[Tunisia]], and the [[West Bank]]. \n\nThe ILF was first established in Afghanistan in 2003, and has expanded its practice to 22 provinces. According to its website, it has provided legal aid services on more than 56,000 cases in the country.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.theilf.org/afghanistan|title=Afghanistan|website=The ILF}}</ref> In 2019, ''[[The Washington Post]]'' published an article about ILF client Brishna, who was accused of murdering her son.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/world/asia_pacific/in-male-dominated-afghanistan-justice-for-women-is-complicated/2019/06/22/e9cf1884-91f5-11e9-956a-88c291ab5c38_story.html|title=In male-dominated Afghanistan, justice for women is complicated|website=Washington Post}}</ref> In that same year, the ILF launched a partnership with [[Ministry of Justice (Afghanistan)|Afghanistan\u2019s Ministry of Justice]] (MoJ) to expand the reach of legal aid and accelerate progress in achieving [[Sustainable Development Goal 16|UN Sustainable Development Goal 16]], justice for all. <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://sustainabledevelopment.un.org/partnership/?p=35414,|title=Strengthening Afghanistan's Legal Aid System, #SDGAction35414}}</ref> Also in 2019, the ILF won the first annual Rule of Law Competition <ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.ili.org/about/news/1066-announcement-of-winners-of-urola%E2%80%99s-first-annual-rule-of-law-competition.html?fbclid=IwAR29MOhFYpWaMMvx71e1mL8Oqo8E0wTeb7ZEvei-QyCyg-QIu_O5Y5RhVzM|title=Announcement of Winners of UROLA\u2019s First Annual Rule of Law Competition|website=www.ili.org}}</ref>, hosted by the United Rule of Law Appeal (UROLA), for its work in Afghanistan.\n\nThe ILF started operating in Myanmar in 2017, where it is active in five regions and staff have worked on more than 300 cases.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.theilf.org/myanmar|title=Myanmar|website=The ILF}}</ref> In 2019, it partnered with [[UNICEF|UNICEF Myanmar]] to support the implementation of the Child Rights Law, connecting young people with juvenile defense lawyers.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.unicef.org/myanmar/press-releases/international-legal-foundation-and-unicef-myanmar-join-forces-protect-children|title=The International Legal Foundation and UNICEF Myanmar join forces to protect children in conflict with the law|website=www.unicef.org}}</ref>\n\nThe ILF began work in Nepal in 2008, where it has worked on an estimated 7,500 cases across five districts.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.theilf.org/nepal|title=Nepal|website=The ILF}}</ref> In 2017, the Nepal program became locally-led, and was independently registered as the Public Defender Society of Nepal (PDS-Nepal).<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://pdsnepal.org/content/who-we-are|title=Public Defender Society: Mission and Story|website=pdsnepal.org}}</ref>\n\nThe ILF began work in the West Bank in 2010, opening its first office in [[Ramallah]].<ref name=\"International Legal Foundation, West Bank\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.theilf.org/west-bank|title=West Bank|website=The ILF}}</ref> According to its website, staff have worked on more than 4,000 cases across 11 governorates.<ref name=\"International Legal Foundation, West Bank\" />\n\nThe ILF began its program in Tunisia in 2015.<ref name=\"International Legal Foundation, Tunisia\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.theilf.org/tunisia|title=Tunisia|website=The ILF}}</ref> In 2020, the [[Tunis]] office took on its 500th case.<ref name=\"International Legal Foundation, Tunisia\" />\n\n=== United Nations ===\nThe ILF works alongside [[List of specialized agencies of the United Nations|United Nations agencies]] in a number of ways. The ILF actively participates in the [[United Nations Congress on Crime Prevention and Criminal Justice|UN Commission on Crime Prevention and Criminal Justice]]<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.unodc.org/documents/commissions/CCPCJ/19-02848_CCPCJ_2019_Programme_ebook_NEW.pdf|title=UNITED NATIONS COMMISSION ON CRIME PREVENTION AND CRIMINAL JUSTICE, 28th Session. \"CCPCJ 2019 Programme\". Page 10.}}</ref> <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.unodc.org/documents/commissions/CCPCJ/19-02848_CCPCJ_2019_Programme_ebook_NEW.pdf|title=UNITED NATIONS COMMISSION ON CRIME PREVENTION AND CRIMINAL JUSTICE, Twenty-fifth Session. \"CCPCJ Programme 2016\". Page 4.}}</ref> <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.unodc.org/documents/commissions/CCPCJ/19-02848_CCPCJ_2019_Programme_ebook_NEW.pdf|title=UNITED NATIONS COMMISSION ON CRIME PREVENTION AND CRIMINAL JUSTICE, TWENTY-SECOND SESSION. \"Side_Events_Programme_22_CCPCJ_2013\". Page 4.}}</ref>, and retains consultative status with the [[United Nations Economic and Social Council]] (ECOSOC).<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://esango.un.org/civilsociety/consultativeStatusSummary.do?profileCode=615040|title=United Nations Civil Society Participation (iCSO) \u2013 Login|website=esango.un.org}}</ref>\n\n=== International Legal Aid Conference ===\nIn 2014, the ILF co-founded the biennial International Conference on Access to Legal Aid in Criminal Justice Systems (ILAC) with the Open Society Justice Initiative (OSJI), the [[United Nations Development Programme]] (UNDP), and the [[United Nations Office on Drugs and Crime]] (UNODC).<ref name=\"About the ILAC\">{{Cite web|url=http://ilac2018.ge/|title=ILAC - Homepage|website=ilac2018.ge}}</ref> The conference highlights \u201cglobal efforts to implement the United Nations Principles and Guidelines on Access to Legal Aid in Criminal Justice Systems, which provide that States should put in place a comprehensive legal aid system.\u201d <ref name=\"About the ILAC\" />\nILAC has been held in the following locations: [[Johannesburg]], South Africa (2014),<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.unodc.org/pdf/criminal_justice/2014_Johannesburg_Declaration_on_Implementation_of_UNPGLA.pdf|title=The Johannesburg Declaration on the Implementation of the United Nations Principles and Guidelines on Access to Legal Aid in Criminal Justice Systems}}</ref> [[Buenos Aires]], Argentina  (2016),<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.unodc.org/documents/justice-and-prison-reform/LegalAid/E_CN15_2017_CRP2_e_V1703525.pdf|title=Outcome of the Second International Conference on Access to Legal Aid in Criminal Justice Systems, held in Buenos Aires, Argentina, 15-17 November 2016}}</ref> and [[Tbilisi]], Georgia (2018).<ref name=\"About the ILAC\" /> The 4th ILAC is scheduled to be held in [[Rio de Janeiro]], Brazil in September 2020.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://ilac2020.rj.def.br/|title=ILAC 2020 - 4\u00ba International Conference on Access to Legal Aid Criminal Justice Systems|website=ilac2020.rj.def.br}}</ref>\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n*[http://www.theilf.org International Legal Foundation Official Website]\n\n[[Category:International nongovernmental organizations]]\n__INDEX__\n", "text_old": "{{DISPLAYTITLE:The International Legal Foundation}}\n\n'''[[The]] International Legal Foundation (ILF)''' is an [[international non-governmental organization]] founded in 2001. It is focused on establishing and strengthening criminal legal aid systems around the world. In addition to its technical assistance work with foreign governments, the ILF provides direct legal aid services through its multiple in-country offices. To date, ILF lawyers have defended more than 60,000 accused individuals worldwide.\n\n== Founding ==\nWhile serving as an observer to the [[Rwandan genocide|Rwandan genocide trials]], attorney Natalie Rea noticed there were \u201ca handful\u201d defense lawyers available<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://soundslikeportraits.com/natalie-rea-lawyer|title=Sounds Like Portraits: Natalie Rea, criminal defense lawyer: 'I basically don't trust authority\"|website=soundslikeportraits.com}}</ref> to represent the over 70,000 incarcerated at Kigali Central Prison. <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=5NdtfmzesHc|title=RWANDA: REPORT FROM KIGALI CENTRAL PRISON, AP Archive}}</ref> She returned home to the [[United States]] and founded Legal Aid Rwanda <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://dev2019.oakfnd.org/international-human-rights-heroes-natalie-rea/|title=International Human Rights Heroes: NATALIE REA|date=June 20, 2016}}</ref>, which recruited lawyers to travel to [[Rwanda]] and provide pretrial defense. In 2001, Rea founded the International Legal Foundation. Rea created the ILF to address legal aid crises in foreign countries, and expand criminal defen